*LA PAZ, July 15 (Reuters) - Popular Bolivian soccer club
*The Strongest Thursday announced it had laid-off its whole team
*after players staged a week-long strike to demand three months
*worth of back wages.
*In announcing the decision, The Strongest's President Jorge
*Sfeir told reporters players had shown "lack of respect" when
*they did not attend a conciliatory meeting. 
*Vidal Gonzalez, a representative for the more than 20
*players fired, said the only solution to the conflict was for
*them to quickly get their salaries "cash in hand."
*Former Argentine soccer star Mario Kempes was hired last
*month as a coach in a bid to bail out The Strongest, which
*ended next to last in the local Apertura tournament disputed in
*the first half of the year.


Season: 1999 
Stage: Clausura


*will be played in two groups of six, all teams playing the other teams
*in the same group as well as two "derby" matches against teams in the
*other group; after those 12 rounds, the top-3 of each play off in the
*Hexagonal (10 rounds) to crown the Clausura champions.

